<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1900-12-22T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1900-12-22T00:00:00-05:00" n="216" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d216">
                    <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Conger</persName> to Mr.
                                <persName type="to">Hay</persName>.</hi></head>
                    <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg></opener>
                    <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1900-12-22"><hi rend="italic">December 22,
                            1900</hi></date>.</dateline></opener>
                    <p>(Mr. Conger acknowledges the Department’s telegram of the 21st, and reports
                        that he had signed the note that day (22d) after again stating the
                        Department’s views. He adds that the note will be handed on the 24th to
                        Chinese plenipotentiaries.)</p>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>